  "identifier" : {
    "interfaceLanguage" : "swift",
    "url" : "doc:\/\/org.swift.migration.6\/documentation\/Swift-6-Concurrency-Migration-Guide\/RuntimeBehavior"
  },
  "kind" : "article",
  "metadata" : {
    "role" : "article",
    "title" : "Runtime Behavior"
  },
  "primaryContentSections" : [
    {
      "content" : [
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Swift’s concurrency model with a strong focus on async\/await, actors and tasks,",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "means that some patterns from other libraries or concurrency runtimes don’t",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "translate directly into this new model. In this section, we’ll explore common",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "patterns and differences in runtime behavior to be aware of, and how to address",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "them while you migrate your code to Swift concurrency.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Limiting-concurrency-using-Task-Groups",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Limiting concurrency using Task Groups",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Sometimes you may find yourself with a large list of work to be processed.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "While it is possible to just enqueue “all” those work items to a task group like this:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "\/\/ Potentially wasteful -- perhaps this creates thousands of tasks concurrently (?!)",
            "",
            "let lotsOfWork: [Work] = ...",
            "await withTaskGroup(of: Something.self) { group in",
            "  for work in lotsOfWork {",
            "    \/\/ If this is thousands of items, we may end up creating a lot of tasks here.",
            "    group.addTask {",
            "      await work.work()",
            "    }",
            "  }",
            "",
            "  for await result in group {",
            "    process(result) \/\/ process the result somehow, depends on your needs",
            "  }",
            "}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "swift",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "If you expect to deal with hundreds or thousands of items, it might be inefficient to enqueue them all immediately.",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "Creating a task (in ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "addTask",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : ") allocates memory for the task in order to suspend and execute it.",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "While the amount of memory for each task isn’t large, it can be significant when creating thousands of tasks that won’t execute immediately.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "When faced with such a situation, you can manually throttle the number of concurrently added tasks in the group, as follows:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "let lotsOfWork: [Work] = ... ",
            "let maxConcurrentWorkTasks = min(lotsOfWork.count, 10)",
            "assert(maxConcurrentWorkTasks > 0)",
            "",
            "await withTaskGroup(of: Something.self) { group in",
            "    var submittedWork = 0",
            "    for _ in 0..<maxConcurrentWorkTasks {",
            "        group.addTask { \/\/ or 'addTaskUnlessCancelled'",
            "            await lotsOfWork[submittedWork].work() ",
            "        }",
            "        submittedWork += 1",
            "    }",
            "    ",
            "    for await result in group {",
            "        process(result) \/\/ process the result somehow, depends on your needs",
            "    ",
            "        \/\/ Every time we get a result back, check if there's more work we should submit and do so",
            "        if submittedWork < lotsOfWork.count, ",
            "           let remainingWorkItem = lotsOfWork[submittedWork] {",
            "            group.addTask { \/\/ or 'addTaskUnlessCancelled'",
            "                await remainingWorkItem.work() ",
            "            }  ",
            "            submittedWork += 1",
            "        }",
            "    }",
            "}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "swift",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        }
      ],
      "kind" : "content"
    }
